{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:13:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16976"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16976"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.06,0.04,0.87]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9666"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68100"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9666"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53557"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4972"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11153"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12798"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68100"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 32 weeks gestation with her first pregnancy. She has type III female genital mutilation (infibulation) performed in childhood. She has no other medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She consents to deinfibulation during labour but requests re-suturing of the vaginal opening afterwards, expressing anxiety about appearing different. She is accompanied by her husband who supports her request.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The external genitalia shows evidence of type III female genital mutilation with a small posterior opening.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response to her request?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Suggest she seeks the procedure in her home country after delivery","Refer her to another provider who may be willing to perform the procedure","Agree to her request to maintain cultural sensitivity","Explain that re-infibulation is illegal and end the consultation","Explain the legal position and health benefits while providing psychological support"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents an ethically and culturally sensitive situation requiring careful communication. The key is to provide accurate information while maintaining therapeutic rapport and cultural sensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplaining the legal position and health benefits while providing psychological support\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate response. This involves clearly communicating that re-infibulation is illegal in Australia while acknowledging her concerns and offering ongoing psychological support. The discussion should include the health benefits of deinfibulation, including easier childbirth, reduced risk of complications, and improved sexual health.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAgreeing to her request to maintain cultural sensitivity\u003C/strong\u003E would be illegal and unethical. While cultural sensitivity is important, healthcare providers have legal and ethical obligations that cannot be compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExplaining that re-infibulation is illegal and ending the consultation\u003C/strong\u003E fails to address the patient\u0027s underlying concerns and anxieties. This approach could damage the therapeutic relationship and potentially drive the patient to seek unsafe alternatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring her to another provider\u003C/strong\u003E who may perform the procedure would be unethical and potentially illegal as it involves complicity in an illegal act.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuggesting she seeks the procedure in her home country\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate and potentially illegal as it could be considered as encouraging FGM. It also fails to address the underlying health and psychological issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management should include referral to appropriate support services, including psychological support and women\u0027s health services with experience in caring for women with FGM. Ongoing antenatal care should include discussion of deinfibulation timing (whether during labour or earlier in pregnancy) and preparation for birth.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Re-infibulation after delivery is illegal in many jurisdictions including Australia and is considered a form of female genital mutilation","Counselling should be culturally sensitive while clearly explaining legal obligations and health implications","Antenatal care for women with FGM should include discussion of deinfibulation timing and psychological support"],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Female genital mutilation (FGM) [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Female-Genital-Mutilation.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53557"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16976"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53557"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T09:59:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:00:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9666"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68100"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"2166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2166"},"attributes